                <div type="general">
                    <p xml:space="preserve">Mazouna is a small historical town on the Dahra Mountains in the province of Relizane. The population in this mountainous area is of Berber origin – primarily of the Zanata and Maghraoua tribes. Mazouna today is inhabited by both Berber and Arabic speakers.</p>
                    <p xml:space="preserve">After the Arab Muslim conquest, the town developed into a trading centre between the Atlantic Ocean and Tunisia. During the Ottoman era, Mazouna was the first capital of the western <hi rendition="#i">beylik</hi>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="researchHistory">
                    <p xml:space="preserve">Only two studies on the dialect of Mazouna exist: <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:E4HSWX9Z">Elhalimi (1996)</rs> discusses 
               negation, including an analysis of the main negation markers and of the different forms of the enhancement of negation; 
               and <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:4W4IMP3R">Bouhadiba (2016)</rs> presents a short overview of the general phonological 
               features of the dialect of Mazouna, but mainly focuses on lexical issues. The latter article emphasises and 
               analyses the Berber influence on the dialect, and provides information on the foundation and history of Mazouna.</p>
                </div>
